      <section environment="" chapter_type="" type="Section" wbtag="section" title="Homomorphisms" course="Math 2070" chapter="9" num="1" serial="9.1">
        <title environment="title" chapter_type="Week" wbtag="title" scope="section" course="Math 2070" chapter="9" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" serial="" slide="">
          <paragraphs course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="title" wbtag="paragraphs">Homomorphisms</paragraphs>
        </title>
        <slides environment="" chapter_type="">
          <slide environment="" chapter_type="Week" canon_num="3" scope="section" id="s3" slide="3" course="Math 2070" chapter="9" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" chapter_title="" section_title="Homomorphisms">
            <keywords slide="3" environ="slide" chapter="9" course="Math 2070">
              <keyword chapter="9" slide="3">ring homomorphism</keyword>
            </keywords>
            <title environment="title" chapter_type="Week" wbtag="title" scope="section" course="Math 2070" chapter="9" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" serial="" slide="3">
              <paragraphs course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="title" wbtag="paragraphs">Homomorphisms</paragraphs>
            </title>
            <statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Definition" wbtag="defn" num="1" md5="704fa25a13e0cdbd6887e64eb2063e6e" course="Math 2070" chapter="9" slide="3" item="9.1">
              <paragraphs course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="statement" wbtag="paragraphs"> Let $(A, +_A, \cdot_A)$, $(B, +_B, \cdot_B)$ be rings.  A </paragraphs>
              <inline_keyword course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="statement">ring homomorphism</inline_keyword>
              <paragraphs course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="statement" wbtag="paragraphs"> from $A$ to $B$
is a map $\phi: A \rightarrow B$ with the following properties: </paragraphs>
              <col_ol course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="col_ol" wbtag="col_ol">
                <col_li course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="col_ol" wbtag="col_li">
                  <paragraphs course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="col_ol" wbtag="paragraphs"> $\phi(1_A) = 1_B$. </paragraphs>
                </col_li>
                <col_li course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="col_ol" wbtag="col_li">
                  <paragraphs course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="col_ol" wbtag="paragraphs"> $\phi(a_1 +_A a_2) = \phi(a_1) +_B \phi(a_2)$, for all $a_1, a_2 \in A$. </paragraphs>
                </col_li>
                <col_li course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="col_ol" wbtag="col_li">
                  <paragraphs course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="col_ol" wbtag="paragraphs"> $\phi(a_1\cdot_A a_2) = \phi(a_1)\cdot_B \phi(a_2)$, for all $a_1, a_2 \in A$. </paragraphs>
                </col_li>
              </col_ol>
            </statement>
            <newline course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment=""/>
            <paragraphs course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs">Note that if $\phi : A \rightarrow B$ is a homomorphism, then: </paragraphs>
            <col_ol course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="col_ol" wbtag="col_ol">
              <col_li course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="col_ol" wbtag="col_li">
                <paragraphs course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="col_ol" wbtag="paragraphs"> \[
\phi(0_A) + \phi(0_A) = \phi(0_A + 0_A) = \phi(0_A).
\]
Adding $-\phi(0_A)$ to both sides, we have:
\[
\phi(0_A) = 0_B.
\] </paragraphs>
                <comment course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="col_ol">
\[
1 = \phi(1) = \phi(1 + 0) = \phi(1) + \phi(0) = 1 + \phi(0),
\]
</comment>
              </col_li>
              <col_li course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="col_ol" wbtag="col_li">
                <paragraphs course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="col_ol" wbtag="paragraphs"> For all $a \in A$, $0 = \phi(0) = \phi(-a + a) = \phi(-a) + \phi(a)$,
which implies that $\phi(-a) = -\phi(a)$. </paragraphs>
              </col_li>
              <col_li course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="col_ol" wbtag="col_li">
                <paragraphs course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="col_ol" wbtag="paragraphs"> If $u$ is a unit in $A$, then $1 = \phi(u\cdot u^{-1}) = \phi(u)\phi(u^{-1})$,
and $1 = \phi(u^{-1}\cdot u) = \phi(u^{-1})\phi(u)$;
which implies that $\phi(u)$ is a unit, with $\phi(u)^{-1} = \phi(u^{-1})$. </paragraphs>
              </col_li>
            </col_ol>
            <newline course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment=""/>
          </slide>
          <slide environment="" chapter_type="Week" wbtag="slide" canon_num="4" id="s4" slide="4" course="Math 2070" chapter="9" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" chapter_title="" section_title="Homomorphisms">
            <keywords slide="4" environ="slide" chapter="9" course="Math 2070"/>
            <statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Example" wbtag="eg" num="2" md5="52d07ae6b861a310748bece0bf8fcfd2" course="Math 2070" chapter="9" slide="4" item="9.2">
              <paragraphs course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="statement" wbtag="paragraphs"> The map $\phi : \mathbb{Z}\rightarrow \mathbb{Q}$ defined by:
\[
\phi(n) = \frac{n}{1}, \quad n \in \mathbb{Z},
\]
is a homomorphism, since: </paragraphs>
              <col_ol course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="col_ol" wbtag="col_ol">
                <col_li course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="col_ol" wbtag="col_li">
                  <paragraphs course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="col_ol" wbtag="paragraphs"> $\phi(1) = \frac{1}{1} = 1_{\mathbb{Q}}$, </paragraphs>
                </col_li>
                <col_li course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="col_ol" wbtag="col_li">
                  <paragraphs course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="col_ol" wbtag="paragraphs"> $\phi(n +_\mathbb{Z} m)  = \frac{m + n}{1}
= \frac{n}{1} +_{\mathbb{Q}} \frac{m}{1}
= \phi(n) +_{\mathbb{Q}} \phi(m)$. </paragraphs>
                </col_li>
                <col_li course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="col_ol" wbtag="col_li">
                  <paragraphs course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="col_ol" wbtag="paragraphs"> $\phi(n \cdot_\mathbb{Z} m)
= \frac{mn}{1} = \frac{n}{1} \cdot_{\mathbb{Q}} \frac{m}{1}
= \phi(n)\cdot_{\mathbb{Q}} \phi(m).
$ </paragraphs>
                </col_li>
              </col_ol>
            </statement>
            <newline course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment=""/>
          </slide>
          <slide environment="" chapter_type="Week" wbtag="slide" canon_num="5" id="s5" slide="5" course="Math 2070" chapter="9" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" chapter_title="" section_title="Homomorphisms">
            <keywords slide="5" environ="slide" chapter="9" course="Math 2070"/>
            <statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Example" wbtag="eg" num="3" md5="c15b39900366612818ec82f4feca6081" course="Math 2070" chapter="9" slide="5" item="9.3">
              <paragraphs course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="statement" wbtag="paragraphs"> Fix an integer $m$ which is larger than $1$.  For $n \in \mathbb{Z}$, let $\ol{n}$ denote the remainder of the division
of $n$ by $m$.  That is:
\[
n = mq + \bar{n}, \quad 0 \leq \bar{n} &lt; m
\]
Recall that $\mathbb{Z}_m = \{0, 1, 2, \ldots, m - 1\}$ is a ring,
with the addition law defined by:
\[
s +_m t = \ol{s + t},
\]
and the multiplication law defined by:
\[
s\times_m t = \ol{s\cdot t},
\]
for all $s, t \in \mathbb{Z}_m$.  Here, $+$ and $\cdot$ are the usual
addition and multiplication for integers.</paragraphs>
              <newline course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="statement"/>
              <newcol course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="newcol">
                <paragraphs course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="paragraphs"> Define a map $\phi : \mathbb{Z} \rightarrow \mathbb{Z}_m $ as follows:
\[
\phi(n) = \ol{n}, \quad \forall n \in \mathbb{Z}.
\] </paragraphs>
                <collapse course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="collapse">
                  <paragraphs course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="paragraphs"> Then, $\phi$ is a homomorphism. </paragraphs>
                </collapse>
              </newcol>
            </statement>
            <substatement environment="substatement" chapter_type="Week" type="Proof" wbtag="proof" md5="43ab386bf5c750dfd327f1bb0e415205" course="Math 2070" chapter="9" slide="5" of="c15b39900366612818ec82f4feca6081" of-src-course="Math 2070" of-src-chapter="9" of-src-slide="5" of-type="Example" of-item="9.3" of-src-filename="week9.xml" ofmd5="c15b39900366612818ec82f4feca6081" of-serial="">
              <of-title hidden="true">Example 9.3</of-title>
              <newcol course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="newcol">
                <col_ol course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="col_ol" wbtag="col_ol">
                  <col_li course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="col_ol" wbtag="col_li">
                    <paragraphs course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="col_ol" wbtag="paragraphs"> $\phi(1) = \ol{1} = 1$, </paragraphs>
                  </col_li>
                  <col_li course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="col_ol" wbtag="col_li">
                    <paragraphs course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="col_ol" wbtag="paragraphs"> $\phi(s + t) = \ol{s + t} = \ol{\ol{s} + \ol{t}} = \ol{s} +_m \ol{t} = \phi(s) +_m \phi(t)$. </paragraphs>
                  </col_li>
                  <col_li course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="col_ol" wbtag="col_li">
                    <paragraphs course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="col_ol" wbtag="paragraphs"> $\phi(s \cdot t) = \ol{s\cdot t} = \ol{\ol{s}\cdot\ol{t}} = \ol{s}\times_m\ol{t} = \phi(s)\times_m\phi(t)$. </paragraphs>
                  </col_li>
                </col_ol>
                <qed course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol"/>
              </newcol>
            </substatement>
            <newline course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment=""/>
          </slide>
          <slide environment="" chapter_type="Week" wbtag="slide" canon_num="6" id="s6" slide="6" course="Math 2070" chapter="9" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" chapter_title="" section_title="Homomorphisms">
            <keywords slide="6" environ="slide" chapter="9" course="Math 2070"/>
            <statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Example" wbtag="eg" num="4" md5="2152ce3be89ef2f21ec407344bdeffeb" course="Math 2070" chapter="9" slide="6" item="9.4">
              <paragraphs course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="statement" wbtag="paragraphs"> For any ring $R$, define a map $\phi : \mathbb{Z} \rightarrow R$ as follows:
\[
\phi(0) = 0;
\] </paragraphs>
              <newcol course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="newcol">
                <paragraphs course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="paragraphs"> For $n \in \mathbb{N}$,
\[
\phi(n) =  n\cdot 1_R := \underbrace{1_R + 1_R + \cdots + 1_R}_{n\text{ times }};
\] </paragraphs>
                <collapse course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="collapse">
                  <paragraphs course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="paragraphs"> \[
\phi(-n) =  -n\cdot 1_R := n\cdot(-1_R) =  \underbrace{(-1_R) + (-1_R) + \cdots + (-1_R)}_{n\text{ times}}.
\] </paragraphs>
                  <collapse course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="collapse">
                    <paragraphs course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="paragraphs"> The map $\phi$ is a homomorphism. </paragraphs>
                  </collapse>
                </collapse>
              </newcol>
            </statement>
            <substatement environment="substatement" chapter_type="Week" type="Proof" wbtag="proof" md5="ef8fb97d271d5d2e855498ac9a9b41b7" course="Math 2070" chapter="9" slide="6" of="2152ce3be89ef2f21ec407344bdeffeb" of-src-course="Math 2070" of-src-chapter="9" of-src-slide="6" of-type="Example" of-item="9.4" of-src-filename="week9.xml" ofmd5="2152ce3be89ef2f21ec407344bdeffeb" of-serial="">
              <of-title hidden="true">Example 9.4</of-title>
              <newcol course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="newcol">
                <inline_keyword course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol">Exercise.</inline_keyword>
              </newcol>
            </substatement>
            <newline course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment=""/>
          </slide>
          <slide environment="" chapter_type="Week" wbtag="slide" canon_num="7" id="s7" slide="7" course="Math 2070" chapter="9" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" chapter_title="" section_title="Homomorphisms">
            <keywords slide="7" environ="slide" chapter="9" course="Math 2070">
              <keyword chapter="9" slide="7">evaluation homomorphism</keyword>
            </keywords>
            <hc_keyword course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="hc_keyword" class="hidden">evaluation homomorphism</hc_keyword>
            <statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Example" wbtag="eg" num="5" md5="3bca8a74c04e7763a3607fb2fcaadc80" course="Math 2070" chapter="9" slide="7" item="9.5">
              <label wbtag="label" name="eg:evalhomom" type="Example"/>
              <paragraphs course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="statement" wbtag="paragraphs"> Let $R$ be a commutative ring.  For each element $r \in R$,
we may define the </paragraphs>
              <strong xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="statement">
                <paragraphs xmlns="http://www.math.cuhk.edu.hk/~pschan/cranach" course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="statement" wbtag="paragraphs">evaluation map</paragraphs>
              </strong>
              <paragraphs course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="statement" wbtag="paragraphs"> $\phi_r : R[x] \rightarrow R$ as follows:
\[
\phi_r\left(\sum_{k = 0}^n a_k x^k\right) = \sum_{k = 0}^n a_k r^k
\]
The map $\phi_r$ is a ring homomorphism. </paragraphs>
            </statement>
            <substatement environment="substatement" chapter_type="Week" type="Proof" wbtag="proof" md5="7931256defb71d36ad7123edaa465bf1" course="Math 2070" chapter="9" slide="7" of="3bca8a74c04e7763a3607fb2fcaadc80" of-src-course="Math 2070" of-src-chapter="9" of-src-slide="7" of-type="Example" of-item="9.5" of-src-filename="week9.xml" ofmd5="3bca8a74c04e7763a3607fb2fcaadc80" of-serial="">
              <of-title hidden="true">Example 9.5</of-title>
              <em xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="substatement">
                <paragraphs xmlns="http://www.math.cuhk.edu.hk/~pschan/cranach" course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="substatement" wbtag="paragraphs">Discussed in class.</paragraphs>
              </em>
            </substatement>
            <newline course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment=""/>
          </slide>
          <slide environment="" chapter_type="Week" wbtag="slide" canon_num="8" id="s8" slide="8" course="Math 2070" chapter="9" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" chapter_title="" section_title="Homomorphisms">
            <keywords slide="8" environ="slide" chapter="9" course="Math 2070">
              <keyword chapter="9" slide="8">isomorphism</keyword>
              <keyword chapter="9" slide="8">isomorphic</keyword>
            </keywords>
            <statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Definition" wbtag="defn" num="6" md5="e0a2cd2e0446a5405cecb97b9facee7c" course="Math 2070" chapter="9" slide="8" item="9.6">
              <paragraphs course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="statement" wbtag="paragraphs"> If a ring homomorphism $\phi: A \rightarrow B$ is a bijective map, we say that $\phi$ is an </paragraphs>
              <inline_keyword course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="statement">isomorphism</inline_keyword>
              <paragraphs course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="statement" wbtag="paragraphs">,
and that $A$ and $B$ are </paragraphs>
              <inline_keyword course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="statement">isomorphic</inline_keyword>
              <paragraphs course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="statement" wbtag="paragraphs"> as rings. </paragraphs>
            </statement>
            <newline course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment=""/>
            <strong xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="">
              <paragraphs xmlns="http://www.math.cuhk.edu.hk/~pschan/cranach" course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="" wbtag="paragraphs">Notation</paragraphs>
            </strong>
            <newcol course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="newcol">
              <paragraphs course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="paragraphs"> If $A$ and $B$ are isomorphic, we write $A \cong B$. </paragraphs>
            </newcol>
            <newline course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment=""/>
          </slide>
          <slide environment="" chapter_type="Week" wbtag="slide" canon_num="9" id="s9" slide="9" course="Math 2070" chapter="9" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" chapter_title="" section_title="Homomorphisms">
            <keywords slide="9" environ="slide" chapter="9" course="Math 2070"/>
            <statement environment="statement" chapter_type="Week" type="Claim" wbtag="claim" num="7" md5="c805c14632eb7e0540de3e7f1f0f3a32" course="Math 2070" chapter="9" slide="9" item="9.7">
              <paragraphs course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="statement" wbtag="paragraphs"> If $\phi:A \rightarrow B$ is an isomorphism, then $\phi^{-1} : B \rightarrow A$ is an isomorphism. </paragraphs>
            </statement>
            <substatement environment="substatement" chapter_type="Week" type="Proof" wbtag="proof" md5="21627d6d8f7cdde680f210a24da5438e" course="Math 2070" chapter="9" slide="9" of="c805c14632eb7e0540de3e7f1f0f3a32" of-src-course="Math 2070" of-src-chapter="9" of-src-slide="9" of-type="Claim" of-item="9.7" of-src-filename="week9.xml" ofmd5="c805c14632eb7e0540de3e7f1f0f3a32" of-serial="">
              <of-title hidden="true">Claim 9.7</of-title>
              <newcol course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="newcol">
                <paragraphs course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="paragraphs"> Since $\phi$ is bijective, $\phi^{-1}$ is clearly bijective.  It remains to show that $\phi^{-1}$ is a homomorphism: </paragraphs>
                <ol xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" environment="newcol">
                  <li environment="newcol">
                    <paragraphs xmlns="http://www.math.cuhk.edu.hk/~pschan/cranach" course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="paragraphs"> Since $\phi(1_A) = 1_B$, we have $\phi^{-1}(1_B) = \phi^{-1}(\phi(1_A)) = 1_A$. </paragraphs>
                  </li>
                  <li environment="newcol">
                    <paragraphs xmlns="http://www.math.cuhk.edu.hk/~pschan/cranach" course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="paragraphs"> For all $b_1, b_2 \in B$, we have
\begin{multline*}
\phi^{-1}(b_1 + b_2) = \phi^{-1}(\phi(\phi^{-1}(b_1)) + \phi(\phi^{-1}(b_2)))
\\= \phi^{-1}(\phi(\phi^{-1}(b_1) + \phi^{-1}(b_2))) = \phi^{-1}(b_1) + \phi^{-1}(b_2)
\end{multline*} </paragraphs>
                  </li>
                  <li environment="newcol">
                    <paragraphs xmlns="http://www.math.cuhk.edu.hk/~pschan/cranach" course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="paragraphs"> For all $b_1, b_2 \in B$, we have
\begin{multline*}
\phi^{-1}(b_1 \cdot b_2) = \phi^{-1}(\phi(\phi^{-1}(b_1)) \cdot \phi(\phi^{-1}(b_2)))
\\= \phi^{-1}(\phi(\phi^{-1}(b_1) \cdot \phi^{-1}(b_2))) = \phi^{-1}(b_1) \cdot \phi^{-1}(b_2)
\end{multline*} </paragraphs>
                  </li>
                </ol>
                <paragraphs course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol" wbtag="paragraphs"> This shows that $\phi^{-1}$ is a bijective homomorphism. </paragraphs>
                <qed course="Math 2070" chapter="9" chapter_type="" section="1" subsection="" subsubsection="" environment="newcol"/>
              </newcol>
            </substatement>
